Macedonians hold referendum to decide whether to change the country's name
Last Sunday, the Macedonian people held a referendum on changing the name to "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece, which had blocked Macedonia's applications to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of its northern neighbor is a claim to its territory and has barred it from joining NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argued that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not participate in the referendum, and a boycott campaign is questioning whether the minimum participation of 50% is reached for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot paper is: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU, with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to achieve the accession of Macedonia, one of the countries that were created following the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to bodies such as the EU and NATO.
"I have come here today to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means that we all will have a safer life", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of MPs have stated that they will abide by the result of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority in Parliament is required.
The State Election Commission reported that no irregularities had occurred at 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to the 34% recorded in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered people voted.
"I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", declared 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in a referendum in Macedonia on changing the country's name, which would pave the way for it to join the European Union and NATO, in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Skopje Parliament, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents set up by people who would boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we want to join them head on, not through the back door", said Kavadarkov.
We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, like China and Russia, and become part of Eurasian integration.
Prime Minister Zaev says that NATO membership will be accompanied by much-needed investments in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20%.
"I think the vast majority will vote in favour, because more than 80% of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO", Zaev said before depositing his ballot.
Zaev stated that a "yes" would mean the "confirmation of our future".
In a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research, between 30% and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure below the minimum participation required.
According to the results of another survey, conducted by the Macedonian TV channel Telma TV, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote "yes".
For a referendum to be valid, the turnout has to be 50% plus one vote.
A failure to vote would be the first major blow to the pro-Western government's policy since it took office in May last year.
