While Ri took up North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearisation approach for which North Korea would be rewarded as it took steps step by step, his remarks seemed significant in that he did not reject full unilateral denuclearisation, as Pyongyang had already done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has attempted to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to relax tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
