This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of caffeinated, all-night studying.
One academic observed that often the world's top university students are distracted by the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
