In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt's hidden intention was to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now", he said of the emerging firm.
"This is a historic moment".
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow users to create their own "personal online data store" or POD.
It can contain contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all of which are available in a browser at the same time.
What is unique about personal online data storage is that the user is the one who decides who can access certain information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is that the company integrates resources, processes and appropriate skills so that the Solid platform is available to everyone.
The company is currently made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, some on-staff developers contracted to work on the project and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that no one on his team is talking to "Facebook and Google about whether we need to introduce a radical change where all business models are completely void overnight.
"We're not asking them for permission".
In a Saturday post on Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial power and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web integrated into the Solid platform".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Even during the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the World Wide Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web", Berners-Lee added.
