They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Trust for Scotland, responsible for caring for over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten properly trained experts, who conduct surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues on a regular basis.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
