The European team wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
Europe's national team won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the United States national team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, outside Paris, France.
The U.S. has already lost six straight times on European soil and hasn't won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
The European team regained the crown when Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points needed to win the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who fought through most of the tournament, threw the opening shot to water at the par 3 16 hole, which gave the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his series and became one of four players to have achieved 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth was sent off with a 5&4 by the less qualified European player Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world's most qualified player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to Ian Poulter of England, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
The eight-time Ryder Cup winner, Spaniard Sergio Garcia, became the tournament's biggest winner ever, with 25.5 career points.
"I don't normally cry, but today I can't help it.
It's been a very tough year.
Thank you, Thomas, for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so happy, so happy to have the cup back.
The team is the most important thing... and I'm happy to have been able to help", said an excited Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the baton to fellow American John Ram, who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in an individual competition on Sunday.
"I'm incredibly proud to have won Tiger Woods, I grew up watching him", said Rahm, 23.
Woods lost all four of his matches in France and now has a career Ryder Cup record of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players to ever play the game, with 14 major titles won and only behind Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team struggled all weekend to find the routes, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played top-notch golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's frustrating performance: "I'm proud of these players, they've fought.
There was a moment this morning when we pressed the European selection.
We fought.
I take my hat off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
Your 12 players have played very well.
We're going to regroup, work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup committee and we're going to make progress.
I love these 12 players and I'm proud to have been their captain.
He's gonna have to take off his hat.
We have been defeated".
Red tide update: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a lower concentration.
The red tide's proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Spots can be found 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week's situation.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Medium to coastal or offshore concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations offshore in Hillsborough County, deep to high concentrations in Manatee County, mid-to-high depth concentrations in Charlotte County, deep to high depth concentrations offshore in Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation is still being reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the last week in northeast Florida.
